---
import ProjectLayout from '../../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
import ProjectTracker from '../../../components/ProjectTracker/ProjectTracker.tsx';

const lang = 'en';
---

<ProjectLayout lang={lang}>
  <h2 id="before-you-start">Before you start</h2>

  <p>
    This module assumes you've been through the previous sessions — or at least
    picked a <strong>tool</strong> (AI-powered IDE or CLI) and an <strong
      >LLM</strong
    > for your code agent. If you haven't, go back to <a
      href="/ai-native-engineering/en/sessions/tools">Sessions 2</a
    >
    and <a href="/ai-native-engineering/en/sessions/models">3</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    What you'll build: a site that consumes the <strong
      >Deezer public API</strong
    > to search for artists, browse discographies, and view album details. Simple,
    functional, publishable on GitHub Pages.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the project is the vehicle, not the destination. What you'll actually
    learn here is the
    <strong>agentic development workflow</strong> — how to create, plan, build, and
    publish a project using your code agent as a development partner.
  </p>

  <h3>What you need ready</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>A <strong>GitHub</strong> account</li>
    <li>
      Your AI development tool already configured (Cursor, Windsurf, Claude
      Code, etc.)
    </li>
    <li>An LLM configured in your tool (Claude, GPT, Gemini, etc.)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Install the GitHub CLI and GitHub MCP</h3>

  <p>
    The <strong>GitHub CLI</strong> (<code>gh</code>) is GitHub's command-line
    tool. With it, your code agent can create repositories, open PRs, configure
    Pages — all without leaving the terminal. And the <strong>GitHub MCP</strong
    > connects your agent directly to GitHub, giving it native access to issues, PRs,
    and repositories as tools.
  </p>

  <p>
    We strongly recommend installing both before continuing. Ask your agent:
  </p>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt that works:</strong>
    <p>
      "Help me install the GitHub CLI on my operating system and authenticate
      with my GitHub account. Then, help me configure the GitHub MCP in my
      development tool."
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Before moving on, confirm that <code>gh auth status</code> shows your authenticated
      account in the terminal.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="create-repository">Create the repository</h2>

  <p>
    The first real step is creating the project repository. Instead of going to
    github.com and clicking "New repository", you'll ask your agent to do it.
    This is the first practice of the agentic workflow: <strong
      >delegate to the agent tasks it can execute with tools</strong
    >.
  </p>

  <p>
    With the GitHub CLI available, the agent can create the repo, set the
    description, and clone it locally — all in one interaction.
  </p>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-bad">
    <strong>Vague prompt (avoid):</strong>
    <p>"Create a repo for me."</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt with context (use this):</strong>
    <p>
      "Create a public repository on GitHub called 'deezer-explorer' with the
      description 'Site for exploring artists and discographies using the Deezer
      API'. Then clone the repository to my local machine so I can start
      developing."
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    See the difference? The contextual prompt gives the agent everything it
    needs: name, visibility, description, and next step. The vague prompt forces
    the agent to guess — and guessing creates rework.
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      The repository exists on your GitHub and is cloned locally. Verify with <code
        >gh repo view</code
      > in the terminal.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="harness-engineering">Harness Engineering</h2>

  <p>
    Now that you have an empty repository, the next step <strong
      >is not writing code</strong
    >. It's preparing the ground so your agent understands what you're building.
    This is
    <strong>Harness Engineering</strong> — configuring the agent's work system.
  </p>

  <p>
    In Session 5, we saw that the difference between operating well with AI and
    operating poorly comes down to the context you give the agent. The harness
    is exactly that: files that live in the repository and tell the agent who it
    is, what the project does, and what the rules are.
  </p>

  <h3>What to put in the harness</h3>

  <p>
    The most important file is <strong>CLAUDE.md</strong> (or <code
      >AGENTS.md</code
    >, depending on your tool). It's the project's "instruction manual" for the
    agent. It should contain:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>What the project is</strong> — clear description of what's being built
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Stack and technical decisions</strong> — which technologies and why
    </li>
    <li><strong>Development commands</strong> — how to run, test, build</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Editorial rules</strong> — code conventions, patterns to follow
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>What not to do</strong> — pitfalls and decisions already made
    </li>
  </ul>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-bad">
    <strong>Generic harness (avoid):</strong>
    <p>"This is a web project. Use best practices."</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt to create a good harness:</strong>
    <p>
      "Create a CLAUDE.md (or AGENTS.md) file at the project root with the
      following information: This project is a static site that consumes the
      Deezer public API to search artists, list discographies, and show album
      details. The site will be published on GitHub Pages. The stack hasn't been
      decided yet — you'll help me choose. The goal is maximum simplicity.
      Include sections for: project overview, development commands, technical
      decisions, and quality rules."
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Notice we're <strong>not prescribing the stack</strong>. The technology
    choice is part of the agentic workflow — you'll plan this with the agent in
    the next step. The harness documents context and rules, not technical
    details that don't exist yet.
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Your repository has a context file (<code>CLAUDE.md</code>, <code
        >AGENTS.md</code
      >, or equivalent) that describes the project, its goals, and its rules.
      Read the file and confirm it makes sense to you.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="plan-with-agent">Plan with the agent</h2>

  <p>
    With the harness in place, the agent now has context. It's time to plan the
    project before writing any code. Planning is one of the most underrated
    phases of working with AI — most people jump straight to "build it for me"
    and end up with a half-working project.
  </p>

  <h3>Define the requirements</h3>

  <p>The project has three main screens/features:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Artist search</strong> — text field that queries the Deezer API (<code
        >/search/artist?q=name</code
      >) and shows results
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Discography</strong> — selecting an artist shows their album list (<code
        >/artist/&#123;id&#125;/albums</code
      >)
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Album details</strong> — clicking an album shows info like tracklist,
      cover art, and release date (<code>/album/&#123;id&#125;</code>)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Ask the agent for a plan</h3>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Planning prompt:</strong>
    <p>
      "Based on the project's CLAUDE.md, create an implementation plan for the
      Deezer Explorer site. The plan should have clear phases, each with a
      defined scope and acceptance criteria. Consider that the site needs to:
      search artists on the Deezer API, show an artist's discography, display
      album details (tracklist, cover, date), and be publishable on GitHub
      Pages. Suggest the simplest stack that works for this case."
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    The agent will generate a plan. <strong>Read the entire plan</strong>. Don't
    auto-accept. Ask yourself:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Do the phases make sense in this order?</li>
    <li>Is each phase's scope clear and feasible?</li>
    <li>Is the suggested stack simple enough?</li>
    <li>Does anything seem over-engineered?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If something doesn't make sense, <strong>iterate</strong>. Ask the agent to
    adjust. "This phase is too big, split it in two." "I don't want that
    library, suggest something simpler." Planning is iterative — a perfect first
    plan doesn't exist.
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      You have an implementation plan with clear phases, saved in the
      repository. Read the plan and confirm each phase makes sense and is
      actionable.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="build-in-parts">Build in parts (SDD)</h2>

  <p>
    Now comes execution — but with discipline. Instead of asking "build the
    whole project", you'll execute <strong
      >one phase of the plan at a time</strong
    >. This is what we call
    <strong>Spec-Driven Development (SDD)</strong>: each iteration has a defined
    scope, acceptance criteria, and validation before moving on.
  </p>

  <h3>The cycle for each phase</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask the agent to implement the phase</strong> — referencing the plan
      and harness
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Review what was generated</strong> — read the code, run locally, test
      it
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Adjust what's needed</strong> — fix bugs, request refactors, improve
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Update the harness</strong> — if technical decisions were made, document
      them in CLAUDE.md
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Move to the next phase</strong> — only when the current one works
    </li>
  </ol>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt to execute a phase:</strong>
    <p>
      "Implement phase 1 of the implementation plan: [describe the phase].
      Follow the rules in CLAUDE.md. When done, show me how to test that it's
      working."
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Deezer API — quick reference</h3>

  <p>
    The Deezer API is public, requires no authentication, and supports CORS. The
    endpoints your project will use:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>https://api.deezer.com/search/artist?q=name</code> — search artists by
      name
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>https://api.deezer.com/artist/&#123;id&#125;/albums</code> — list an artist's
      albums
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>https://api.deezer.com/album/&#123;id&#125;</code> — album details (tracks,
      cover, date)
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Data comes as JSON and includes images (album covers, artist photos), making
    the visual result look good without extra effort.
  </p>

  <h3>What to watch during the build</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Don't accept code without reading it</strong> — understand what each
      part does
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Test each phase locally</strong> — open the site, click the links, check
      the data loads
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Keep the harness updated</strong> — if the agent picked a library or
      pattern, document it
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One phase at a time</strong> — resist the urge to ask for everything
      at once
    </li>
  </ul>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      The project runs locally, shows data from the Deezer API, and all plan
      phases are implemented. Test searching for an artist, viewing their
      discography, and clicking on an album.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="publish">Publish to GitHub Pages</h2>

  <p>
    Your project works locally. Now it's time to go live. <strong
      >GitHub Pages</strong
    >
    serves static sites directly from your repository — it's free and works perfectly
    for this type of project.
  </p>

  <p>
    Just like the previous steps, you'll ask the agent to configure deployment.
    Most modern stacks have a way to generate static files and configure GitHub
    Actions for automatic deployment.
  </p>

  <div class="prompt-example prompt-good">
    <strong>Prompt to configure deployment:</strong>
    <p>
      "Configure the project for deployment on GitHub Pages. Create a GitHub
      Actions workflow that builds and automatically publishes when I push to
      the main branch. Tell me which settings I need to enable in the
      repository."
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Validating the deployment</h3>

  <p>After the agent configures everything and you push:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Pages</strong> in your GitHub repository</li>
    <li>Confirm the source is set to <strong>GitHub Actions</strong></li>
    <li>
      Wait for the workflow to complete (watch in the <strong>Actions</strong> tab)
    </li>
    <li>
      Visit your site URL (usually <code
        >https://your-username.github.io/deezer-explorer/</code
      >)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Test the features: search for an artist, browse their discography, open an
    album. If everything works on GitHub Pages like it does locally, your
    project is published.
  </p>

  <div class="checkpoint">
    <strong>✓ Checkpoint:</strong>
    <p>
      Your site is published and accessible via the GitHub Pages URL. All three
      features (search, discography, details) work correctly on the published
      site.
    </p>
  </div>

  ---

  <h2 id="interactive-block">Track your progress</h2>

  <ProjectTracker client:visible lang={lang} />

  ---

  <h2 id="takeaway">What to take from here</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Context before code</strong> — the harness is the first artifact, not
      the first component
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan before building</strong> — an iterated plan with the agent prevents
      rework
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One phase at a time</strong> — SDD works because each step is verifiable
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Prompts with context</strong> — interaction quality defines output quality
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Read what the agent generates</strong> — accepting without reading is
      the most common failure
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Publishing is part of the flow</strong> — deployment isn't extra, it's
      the natural conclusion
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You just built a project from scratch to deployment using a code agent. This
    workflow — context, planning, phased execution, validation, publishing — is
    the same one that works in real projects. The scale changes, the process
    doesn't.
  </p>
</ProjectLayout>
